# Binary assets must NEVER be line-ending-normalized.
#
# Git classifies a file as text when it contains no NUL bytes — but some binary
# files have none (e.g. a small, uncompressed signed PDF), so with
# core.autocrlf=true a Windows checkout translates LF->CRLF and shifts every
# byte offset after the first newline. That silently corrupts byte-offset-
# sensitive formats: a signed PDF's xref/ByteRange no longer matches its stored
# location, and pyHanko's STRICT verify fails with "Could not find xref table at
# specified location" (pikepdf and pdf.js reconstruct a broken xref and hide the
# corruption, so only signature verification exposes it — it broke
# e2e-tests/specs/12-signatures.spec.ts on the GitHub windows runner, 5/5, while
# every other spec passed). Marking these `binary` disables EOL translation and
# textual diffing, so every checkout is byte-identical to the committed blob on
# all platforms.

*.pdf   binary
*.pdfx  binary
*.pfx   binary
*.p12   binary
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.icns  binary
*.bmp   binary
*.sig   binary
*.dll   binary
*.exe   binary
*.pyd   binary
*.wasm  binary
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf   binary
*.otf   binary
*.traineddata binary
